                            cannot meet the growing needs of the Internet.
                    </div>
                    <div class="blog_list">
                        <h3>What is Fiber Optics?</h3>
                        <p>Fiber Internet works by splitting files such as movies and games into null packets and some
                            data packets. The laser irradiates one end of a plastic or glass filament with this Morse
                            code-style signal. The "Fibre" is about as thick as the thread of human hair. 
                            A unique shell called cladding holds the rays inside the filament. It bounces off the wall
                            for up to 60 miles, with the other end popping out. The media convertor decodes the optical
                            signal into digital signal that the computer can use.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="benifits">
                        <h3>Advantages of preferring Fiber Optics over Copper wiring: - </h3>


                        <h4>Longer distance </h4>
                        <p>Fiber optic signals are light, so there is little signal loss during transmission, and data
                            can be transmitted at higher speeds and distances. 
                            Fiber lengths range from 300 meters (984.2 feet) to 40 kilometers (24.8 miles), depending on
                            the cable type, wavelength, and network. Fiber optic signals are less amplified than copper
                            signals, which improves cable performance.

                        <h4>Reliable </h4>
                        <p>Fiber optics provide highly reliable data transmission. It is not affected by other
                            environmental factors that affect copper wire. Fiber optic cables can be laid next to
                            industrial plants without hesitation. Therefore, fibers are less susceptible to temperature
                            changes than copper and can be dissolved in water.</p>
                        <h4>Design</h4>
                        <p>
                            Fibre optics is lighter, more flexible, and more durable than copper wire. In addition, the
                            tensile strength of fiber optic cables is up to 10 times that of copper cables. Due to its
                            small size, it is easy to handle and requires even less space in the cable duct. Fiber is
                            still more difficult to terminate than copper wire, but advances in connectors have made it
                            easier to remove.

                            
                            Fiber optics are often easier to test than copper wire.
                        </p>
                        <h4>Migration </h4>
                        <p>The widespread use and low cost of media converters make copper wire to fiber conversion much
                            more accessible. The converter creates a seamless connection and allows you to use your
                            existing hardware. With the expected upgrade, fiber optics can be incorporated into the
                            network. </p>

                        <h4>Norms </h4>
                        <p>Approved in 2001, TIA / EIA-785 provides a cost-effective migration path from 10Mbps Ethernet
                            to 100Mbps Fast Ethernet Overfiber (100BASE-SX). The specification addendum addresses
                            weaknesses in transceiver design. In June 2002, the IEEE approved the IEEE 10 Gigabit
                            Ethernet (10-GbE) specification.
                        </p>

                        <h4>Cost </h4>
                        <p>Fiber optic cables, modules, and equipment costs are slowly declining. Fiber installation
                            costs are higher than copper wire due to the features required for termination. In general,
                            fiber is more expensive than copper in the short term, but it can be cheaper in a long time.
                            Fiber maintenance costs, downtime, and less connection equipment are typically low.
                            Therefore, using fiber reduces the need to rewire to improve network performance.
                        </p>

                        <h4>Bandwidth </h4>
                        <p>Investing in fiber internet will significantly increase your bandwidth capacity. Copper
                            infrastructure and TDM (Time Division Multiplexing) technology are inherently limited.
                            Originally designed to carry only voice calls, bandwidth requirements were not high. For
                            example, the T-1 can only transmit a throughput of 1.5Mbps. 
                            Also, due to the mechanism of electrical signals, many wiring connections are limited by
                            distance. Bandwidth transfer over fiber is invaluable for companies considering migrating
                            voice communications to Voice-over-IP (VoIP).


                        </p>
                        <h4>Secure </h4>
                        <p>Unlike copper, broken or damaged fiber can be detected very quickly. This makes it easier to
                            diagnose and resolve application issues before performance is impacted severely.
                            Additionally, fiber doesnâ€™t short out like copper does, which can result in a fire. These
                            advantages make fiber the safer choice in fiber optic solutions and applications.


                        </p>

                        <h4>Privacy </h4>
                        <p>Your data is secure with fiber optic cable. Fiber optic cables are harder to tap into than
                            copper cables. Hacking attempts in fiber optics are much more likely to be noticed,
                            resulting in quicker response times. With increasing cybersecurity awareness, fiber is
                            promoted as a cost-effective way to quickly improve Internet security.<br><br>
                            So, when choosing internet connectivity, the best option is the Optical Fiber over copper
                            wirings.



                        </p>
